\begin{align*}
6+y&=a,\\
4+5y&=2a.
\end{align*}
Solving the first equation for $a$ gives:
\begin{align*}
a&=6+y.
\end{align*}
Substituting this expression for $a$ into the second equation, we get:
\begin{align*}
4+5y&=2(6+y),\\
4+5y&=12+2y,\\
3y&=8,\\
y&=\frac{8}{3}.
\end{align*}
Substituting this value of $y$ back into the first equation, we get:
\begin{align*}
a&=6+\frac{8}{3},\\
a&=\frac{26}{3}.
\end{align*}
</answer>

