response:
 Given that 1 liter is equal to 1000 milliliters, we can find out how manyReceipts are in a liter by dividing 1000 milliliters by the volume of one drip. The volume of one drip is given as $\frac{1}{4}$ of a milliliter. 
Springy Tom, here goes the math:
\begin{align}
\text{Total Drips in a Liter} &= \frac{1000 \text{ milliliters}}{\frac{1}{4} \text{ milliliter per drip}} \\
&= 1000 \text{ milliliters} \times \frac{4}{1} \text{ drip per milliliter} \\
&= 4000 \text{ drips}
\end{align}
